ing cabinets in this category include at least a basic lock, but the security level varies, so check specifically if you need genuine document security versus just closed drawers.</p>\n</div>\n<div style=\"background:#f9f9fb;border-radius:10px;padding:16px;\">\n<p style=\"margin:0 0 6px 0;font-weight:600;color:#290342;\">How many drawers do I actually need?</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0;color:#333;\">2-drawer cabinets suit light personal use or a small home office; 3-4 drawer cabinets handle a full home office or small business archive - oversizing wastes floor space, so measure your actual current document volume rather than buying for hypothetical future growth.</p>\n</div>\n<div style=\"background:#f9f9fb;border-radius:10px;padding:16px;\">\n<p style=\"margin:0 0 6px 0;font-weight:600;color:#290342;\">Are metal or wood filing cabinets more durable?</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0;color:#333;\">Metal cabinets generally hold up better to heavy daily use and are more fire/moisture resistant; wood or laminate cabinets blend better with home office furniture but are more prone to wear on drawer glides over years of heavy use.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p><em>As an Amazon Associate, ChampionsReviews.com earns from qualifying purchases. All prices, ratings, and review counts shown are pulled directly from Amazon.com listings at the time of publishing and are subject to change. Pros, cons, and recommendations above are editorial analysis based on this listed data, not independent hands-on testing.</em></p>\n"
